Plague provides the title of this book. Zaretsky delves into these writers to uncover lessons that can provide deeper insight into our pandemic era. At the same time, he goes beyond the literature to invoke his own experience of the tragedy that enveloped his Texas nursing home, one which first took the form of chronic loneliness and then, inevitably, the deaths of many residents whom we come to know through Zaretsky’s stories. In doing so, Zaretsky shows the power of great literature to connect directly to one’s own life in a different moment and time. For all of us still struggling to comprehend this pandemic and its toll, Zaretsky serves as a thoughtful and down-to-earth guide to the many ways we can come to know and make peace with human suffering.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCOVID-19 Pandemic, 2020-xSocial aspects. 0aEpidemics in literature. 0aEuropean literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aPlague in literature. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh  anursing homes, care, caregiving, healthcare, health, healthy, reading, plague, volunteer work, volunteering, pandemic, disease, illness, grief, mourning, loss, death, dying, covid-19, coronavirus, history, historical context, albert camus, mary shelley, daniel defoe, michel de montaigne, marcus aurelius, thucydides, literature, literary works, loneliness, human suffering, humanity, epidemics, london, athens, bubonic, la peste brune, antonine.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2022 Englishz978311099375208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural,